# Don't Get Around Much Anymore

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia

Jump to: navigation, search

"Don't Get Around Much Anymore"  
---  
[Song](/wiki/Song "Song") by Duke Ellington  
Published | [1940](/wiki/1940_in_music "1940 in music")  
[Songwriter(s)](/wiki/Songwriter "Songwriter") | [Duke Ellington](/wiki/Duke_Ellington "Duke Ellington"), [Bob Russell](/wiki/Bob_Russell_\(songwriter\) "Bob Russell \(songwriter\)")  
  
"**Don 't Get Around Much Anymore**" is a [jazz standard](/wiki/Jazz_standard
"Jazz standard") with music by [Duke Ellington](/wiki/Duke_Ellington "Duke
Ellington") and lyrics by [Bob Russell](/wiki/Bob_Russell_\(songwriter\) "Bob
Russell \(songwriter\)"). The tune was originally called "Never No Lament" and
was first recorded by Ellington in 1940 as a [big-band](/wiki/Big-band "Big-
band") [instrumental](/wiki/Instrumental "Instrumental"). Russell's lyrics and
the new title were added in 1942.

Two different recordings of "Don't Get Around Much Anymore", one by [The Ink
Spots](/wiki/The_Ink_Spots "The Ink Spots") and the other by Ellington's own
band, reached #1 on the [R&B chart](/wiki/R%26B_chart "R&B chart") in the US
in 1943. Both were top-ten pop records, along with a version by [Glen
Gray](/wiki/Glen_Gray "Glen Gray"). The Duke Ellington version reached #8 on
the pop chart.[1]
